<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-186-093 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 632 937</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications News  April 1991 v28 n4 p26(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cellular provides safety net for New Jersey handicapped. (Cellularand Two-way Radio)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>New Jersey now requires buses used by the Division ofDevelopmental Disabilities (DDD) to transport disabled students tobe equipped with a cellular telephone in order to summon emergencyhelp.andP;  Buses transporting the disabled often had to stop at publicpay phones to request help since many of the disabled students arein fragile health.andP;  Requiring the buses to have cellular phonesimproves the bus drivers' ability to summon aid and gives thedisabled students' parents peace of mind.andP;  The state investigatedtwo-way radio and cellular telephones, and chose cellulartelephones for their price advantages.andP;  DDD special assistant LeeB. Berkey states that two-way radios would have cost $400,000,compared to the $180,000 it cost to install the cellulartechnology on DDD buses.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Cellular radioHandicappedTelecommunicationsTransportation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>